read that stuff.
Are you a scientist?.

242
00:20:47,039 --> 00:20:50,787
I've done similar research
based on a polymer
skin substitute.

243
00:20:50,876 --> 00:20:54,624
Like you, though,
I've had problems with
disintegration in UV light.

244
00:20:54,713 --> 00:20:59,209
Anyway, I've put my findings
on disk, and I'd be honored
if you could take a look.

245
00:21:00,427 --> 00:21:02,965
Certainly.
Excellent.
We'll talk.

246
00:21:05,057 --> 00:21:06,884
I didn't get your name.

247
00:21:11,146 --> 00:21:13,103
[ Exhales ]

248
00:21:13,649 --> 00:21:16,104
* [ Humming ]

249
00:21:23,992 --> 00:21:26,946
Here you go, boss.
Just the way you like 'em.

250
00:21:36,004 --> 00:21:39,005
- [ Glass Shatters]
- [ Clapping]

251
00:21:40,342 --> 00:21:43,296
- Good, boss.
- [ Clapping Continues ]

252
00:21:47,933 --> 00:21:51,978
You wanted
to see me, boss?.
Rollo! Yes. Do join us.

253
00:21:58,318 --> 00:22:01,853
I understand
you spoke to the owner
of the factory yesterday.

254
00:22:01,947 --> 00:22:03,525
Uh, yeah.

255
00:22:03,615 --> 00:22:05,359
He ain't sellin'.

256
00:22:07,995 --> 00:22:11,411
- It's unfortunate Brinkman
declined our offer.
- Yeah.

257
00:22:11,498 --> 00:22:14,452
So, uh,
what's the plan, boss?

258
00:22:16,295 --> 00:22:19,664
I had an interesting
conversation with our
Colombian friends today.

259
00:22:19,756 --> 00:22:23,588
Do you know
what they told me?.
Mr. Durant, I can explain--

260
00:22:23,677 --> 00:22:26,927
They told me you were taking
a five-percent bonus on
all our drug shipments.

261
00:22:27,014 --> 00:22:31,058
- That was nothin', Mr. Durant.
- Edward, how long was I
in my coma?.

262
00:22:31,143 --> 00:22:35,437
878 days, 1 2 hours
and 1 6 minutes, Mr. Durant.

263
00:22:35,522 --> 00:22:38,013
800 days,
two shipments a week,

264
00:22:38,108 --> 00:22:41,773
each shipment worth, say,
ten million dollars
on the street,

265
00:22:41,862 --> 00:22:44,400
minus the problems
with the exchange rate.

266
00:22:44,489 --> 00:22:49,614
- What do you say that might
add up to, Edward?.
- $27,280,000...

267
00:22:49,703 --> 00:22:51,909
and 1 7 cents.

268
00:22:54,124 --> 00:22:56,615
Aah!
[ Groaning ]

269
00:22:58,295 --> 00:23:01,415
[ Grunting ]
Come on! Come on!

270
00:23:01,507 --> 00:23:03,914
Come on. Get in!
[ Grunting ]

271
00:23:05,219 --> 00:23:08,634
- Wh-- No! No!
- Buckle up.

272
00:23:08,722 --> 00:23:13,965
- Where's my fucking money?.
- C-Cayman Bank of Commerce.
I-I got an account there.

273
00:23:14,061 --> 00:23:16,978
I was gonna tell you.
It was gonna be a surprise!

274
00:23:17,064 --> 00:23:19,389
Oh, I'm surprised.
Can't you tell?.

275
00:23:19,483 --> 00:23:23,066
- [ Giggles ]
- [Durant ] And now
I have a surprise for you.

276
00:23:23,153 --> 00:23:25,988
[ Screaming ]

277
00:23:27,658 --> 00:23:29,567
[ Screaming Continues ]

278
00:23:37,751 --> 00:23:40,622
Always replace
your divots, Rollo.

279
00:23:50,264 --> 00:23:53,383
Seventeen over the--
No, no, no, eighteen.
Eighteen.

280
00:23:53,475 --> 00:23:55,931
[ Footsteps ]

281
00:23:59,690 --> 00:24:02,774
[ Beeping]
Chow time, Doc.

282
00:24:02,860 --> 00:24:05,777
So, what are we
having this evening?.

283
00:24:05,863 --> 00:24:08,614
Lobster florentine?.
Beef Wellington.

284
00:24:08,699 --> 00:24:12,483
Perhaps grilled ahi
on a bed of Belgian endive.

285
00:24:12,578 --> 00:24:14,451
No, your old favorite,
Doc.

286
00:24:15,539 --> 00:24:17,531
I hate meat loaf!

287
00:24:17,624 --> 00:24:19,950
[Men Screaming]

288
00:24:37,269 --> 00:24:39,143
Dr. Hathaway, I presume.

289
00:24:41,106 --> 00:24:44,557
Ahh.
[ Belches ]

290
00:24:47,112 --> 00:24:50,528
So, what am I
doing here, Robert?.

291
00:24:50,616 --> 00:24:55,361
You didn't go to the trouble
of breaking me out to
feed me a home-cooked meal.

292
00:24:55,454 --> 00:24:59,368
Well, there aren't many
scientists with your vision,
your technical expertise.

293
00:25:00,959 --> 00:25:03,877
What you mean is,
there aren't many men...

294
00:25:03,962 --> 00:25:06,880
who could build
a hydrogen bomb
in their garage.

295
00:25:06,965 --> 00:25:10,381
You were working on something
before your untimely arrest.

296
00:25:10,469 --> 00:25:13,719
A man-portable,
air-cooled, semi-automatic
particle beam weapon.

297
00:25:13,805 --> 00:25:15,715
Guns for the new century.

298
00:25:15,807 --> 00:25:17,847
Weapons
of devastating firepower.

299
00:25:17,935 --> 00:25:22,347
If we can build a better
assault rifle, the world
will beat a path to our door.

300
00:25:22,439 --> 00:25:26,353
- But all you lack
is the technology.
- And that's where you come in.

301
00:25:28,904 --> 00:25:31,027
Power is going to be
a problem.

302
00:25:32,324 --> 00:25:35,574
That weapon requires
a lot of energy.

303
00:25:35,661 --> 00:25:39,908
You let me worry about that.
Are you interested?.

304
00:25:39,998 --> 00:25:43,830
- I still have my brainchild
stored away.
- Then we have a deal.

305
00:25:46,839 --> 00:25:50,042
I hope you saved room
for dessert.

306
00:25:50,133 --> 00:25:52,375
[Hathaway]
Ladies!

307
00:25:52,469 --> 00:25:54,378
Oh.

308
00:25:58,016 --> 00:26:00,139
You drive a hard bargain.

309
00:26:10,028 --> 00:26:12,436
You shouldn't
have to ask!
That's--

310
00:26:12,531 --> 00:26:15,448
I won't have it!
It's not your choice!

311
00:26:15,534 --> 00:26:17,443
[Door Opens ]

312
00:26:23,959 --> 00:26:27,624
I'm sorry.
The gate was open.
[ Woman ]
I was just leaving.

313
00:26:27,713 --> 00:26:30,500
David, I'll talk
to you later.

314
00:26:33,010 --> 00:26:35,002
Hi, I'm Laurie.

315
00:26:35,095 --> 00:26:37,800
Peyton.
Nice to meet you,
Peyton.

316
00:26:37,890 --> 00:26:39,799
You too.

317
00:26:40,893 --> 00:26:43,929
So, it's, uh...
Peyton.

318
00:26:45,397 --> 00:26:48,848
Yeah. Was, uh, that,
your, uh, girlfriend?.

319
00:26:50,652 --> 00:26:52,562
No, uh, sister.

320
00:26:54,740 --> 00:26:58,156
This is an amazing place
you've built here.

321
00:26:58,243 --> 00:27:00,319
Yeah. It's got
a lot of history.

322
00:27:00,412 --> 00:27:04,161
My father tried
to make a go of it
through the war and beyond.

323
00:27:04,249 --> 00:27:08,958
He was pioneering research
in conventional and atomic
power applications.

324
00:27:09,046 --> 00:27:13,209
I guess you could say
he was a little bit
ahead of his time.

325
00:27:13,300 --> 00:27:15,708
Yeah.

326
00:27:15,802 --> 00:27:17,842
He passed away
three years ago.

327
00:27:19,598 --> 00:27:23,133
I think he died when they
turned the lights out
in this place.

328
00:27:23,227 --> 00:27:25,136
I'm sorry to hear that.

329
00:27:26,897 --> 00:27:30,895
It's okay. You know,
I always knew that I
would come back here.

330
00:27:30,943 --> 00:27:35,154
I mean, this place,
it just feels like... home.

331
00:27:35,239 --> 00:27:38,358
You know, my father's spirit
was driven by his strength.

332
00:27:38,450 --> 00:27:41,985
He even harnessed a power
supply that was big enough
to drive a small city.

333
00:27:42,079 --> 00:27:44,534
It inspires me
to try great things.

334
00:27:44,623 --> 00:27:46,580
Like what?.

335
00:27:48,085 --> 00:27:52,379
I want to rekindle a kind
of scientific renaissance.

336
00:27:52,464 --> 00:27:55,382
A place where scientists
can come from all over
the world and work...

337
00:27:55,467 --> 00:28:00,425
outside of the constraints
of established funding.
You know?.

338
00:28:01,557 --> 00:28:03,964
I mean, just
look around this place.

339
00:28:04,059 --> 00:28:07,179
Just imagine...
the possibilities in here.

340
00:28:10,440 --> 00:28:12,433
That's, uh...

341
00:28:12,526 --> 00:28:14,483
the dream, you know.

342
00:28:15,529 --> 00:28:18,067
It's important
to have a dream.

343
00:28:18,156 --> 00:28:20,066
I'm impressed.

344
00:28:21,827 --> 00:28:24,069
I'm impressed with you.

345
00:28:24,162 --> 00:28:27,366
The work on those disks--
brilliant.

346
00:28:27,457 --> 00:28:30,162
Let me show you something.
Come on.

347
00:28:31,920 --> 00:28:35,621
There was similar work
to yours published
a few years back.

348
00:28:35,716 --> 00:28:38,041
It was by a scientist
named...

349
00:28:38,135 --> 00:28:40,127
Westlake.
You know him?

350
00:28:40,220 --> 00:28:42,509
I was familiar
with his work.

351
00:28:42,598 --> 00:28:45,515
I ran the formulas you used
for the polymer base.

352
00:28:45,601 --> 00:28:49,052
I used a similar one myself
a few months back.
It didn't work either.

353
00:28:49,146 --> 00:28:53,013
But I was using
negatively-charged ions.
You used a silicon base?.

354
00:28:53,108 --> 00:28:55,231
No, no. Carbon.

355
00:28:55,319 --> 00:28:58,604
But last night
I ran a sample set
using your formulas,

356
00:28:58,697 --> 00:29:01,568
only I reversed the charge
of the ions.

357
00:29:02,659 --> 00:29:05,863
And in full exposure
to sunlight,

358
00:29:05,954 --> 00:29:10,497
this little sucker
lasted 1 73 minutes.

359
00:29:10,584 --> 00:29:12,992
1 73 minutes?.

360
00:29:13,086 --> 00:29:15,624
[ Both Laughing ]

361
00:29:16,673 --> 00:29:18,583
You did it!

362
00:29:18,675 --> 00:29:20,633
You beat
the 99-minute barrier!

363
00:29:21,762 --> 00:29:24,846
- You did it.
- Hey, it's only one sample.

364
00:29:24,932 --> 00:29:29,428
But I think together we
could crack the structure for
a permanently stable polymer.

365
00:29:30,854 --> 00:29:34,223
That is, if you'd be
interested in a partnership.

366
00:29:34,316 --> 00:29:38,100
Oh, I'm interested.
I'm very interested.

367
00:29:38,195 --> 00:29:42,656
Only to crack it,
we're gonna need a digital
spectrochronometer.

368
00:29:42,741 --> 00:29:44,864
One of the new 1 000 models.

369
00:29:44,952 --> 00:29:47,906
They're expensive.
No, don't worry.
Money's not a problem.

370
00:29:47,996 --> 00:29:53,785
- What, do you have a grant?.
- No, I, uh, I get donations
from the community.

371
00:29:55,879 --> 00:29:58,417
Partners, then?.

372
00:30:02,845 --> 00:30:05,632
Partners.
[ Laughs ]

373
00:30:05,722 --> 00:30:08,095
When can we start?.
[Beeping]

374
00:30:10,686 --> 00:30:13,259
I have to see somebody.
I have an appointment.

375
00:30:13,355 --> 00:30:16,439
I'll talk to you soon.
This is fantastic.
Thank you.

376
00:30:17,526 --> 00:30:19,269
This is fantastic!

377
00:30:19,361 --> 00:30:21,270
Thank you,
Dr. Brinkman!

378
00:30:21,363 --> 00:30:23,272
Partners, huh?.
[ Laughing ]

379
00:30:23,574 --> 00:30:26,278
[ Beeping ]
[Television, Indistinct ]

380
00:30:26,368 --> 00:30:30,117
Here, kitty, kitty.
Come on.

381
00:30:30,205 --> 00:30:32,447
I have a surprise.
[ Beeping Continues ]

382
00:30:32,541 --> 00:30:34,948
I'd like you to meet
a friend of mine.

383
00:30:35,043 --> 00:30:38,163
- Ah, there you are!
[ Laughing ]
- [ Cat Yowling ]

384
00:30:40,549 --> 00:30:42,956
Come on. Come on.
[ Woman On Television ]
Thank you for that report.

385
00:30:43,051 --> 00:30:46,966
While there's no question
as to the victim's identity,
questions remain unanswered.

386
00:30:49,224 --> 00:30:51,300
Be careful. He bites.

387
00:30:51,393 --> 00:30:55,307
[ Woman ]... the criminal empire
built by Robert G. Durant, who
disappeared a few years ago.

388
00:30:55,397 --> 00:30:57,306
Latham, suspected
in several gangland slayings,

389
00:30:57,399 --> 00:31:01,812
had emerged as a brutal
lord of the underworld;
tonight his reign is over.

390
00:31:01,904 --> 00:31:05,486
His death, police believe,
may signal that there is
more than one contender...

391
00:31:05,574 --> 00:31:09,157
to the throne left vacant
by Robert Durant.

392
00:31:09,244 --> 00:31:13,906
- I'll continue to bring you
more on this story.
- No! David!

393
00:31:17,211 --> 00:31:19,120
Okay.

394
00:31:19,213 --> 00:31:22,379
The D.I.N.I. samples
have stabilized.

395
00:31:23,675 --> 00:31:25,882
The cell membranes--

396
00:31:27,304 --> 00:31:30,590
Mmm--
remain elastic.

397
00:31:31,767 --> 00:31:34,768
And there appears to be
no breakdown...

398
00:31:34,853 --> 00:31:37,225
in cell structure...

399
00:31:37,314 --> 00:31:40,101
or activity after...

400
00:31:41,693 --> 00:31:43,651
98 minutes.

401
00:31:44,738 --> 00:31:47,027
Okay.

402
00:31:47,115 --> 00:31:49,441
Let's go for the record,
baby.

403
00:31:51,203 --> 00:31:53,610
[ Telephone Rings ]

404
00:31:56,375 --> 00:31:58,284
Dr. Brinkman, I presume.

405
00:32:00,754 --> 00:32:02,877
- [ Chuckles ]
- Aah!

406
00:32:04,591 --> 00:32:07,082
- No!
- I believe
you're acquainted...

407
00:32:07,177 --> 00:32:10,214
- with a former associate
of mine, Rollo Latham.
- Former?.

408
00:32:10,305 --> 00:32:12,975
Mr. Latham and I
had a falling out.

409
00:32:16,687 --> 00:32:19,178
[ Male Computer Voice ]
Good evening, Dr. Westlake.

410
00:32:29,658 --> 00:32:32,066
Full throttle! Come on!

411
00:32:32,160 --> 00:32:35,245
All you have to do...
is sign.

412
00:32:35,330 --> 00:32:38,117
[ Panting ]
I told him, I'll tell you.

413
00:32:39,168 --> 00:32:41,077
This property's
not for sale.

414
00:32:41,170 --> 00:32:45,084
Rollo made it
very clear that money
was of no interest to you.

415
00:32:45,174 --> 00:32:47,380
I've asked Mr. Druganov
to resume negotiations...

416
00:32:47,467 --> 00:32:50,587
with an incentive you'll
find much more compelling.

417
00:32:53,265 --> 00:32:58,093
One more move, and I'll
perform laser surgery
on each one of you guys.

418
00:32:58,187 --> 00:33:01,437
- Now leave!
- A regular Luke Skywalker.

419
00:33:01,523 --> 00:33:03,730
- Yeah?.
- Whoa!

420
00:33:09,948 --> 00:33:11,692
[ Chuckles ]

421
00:33:18,040 --> 00:33:21,539
Ivan?. Please teach
Dr. Brinkman some manners.

422
00:33:26,798 --> 00:33:30,002
- Are we all clear?.
- [ Computer ] Access
terranean level, tunnel B.

423
00:33:32,054 --> 00:33:35,138
[ Screaming ]

424
00:33:35,224 --> 00:33:37,133
My work! My work!

425
00:33:37,226 --> 00:33:39,598
What's it going to take,
Dr. Brinkman?.

426
00:33:40,812 --> 00:33:43,517
[ Grunting, Yelling ]

427
00:33:46,735 --> 00:33:49,191
[ Groaning ]
[ Laughing, Yelling ]

428
00:33:51,198 --> 00:33:54,567
- [Eddie Giggling]
- [ Muttering In Russian ]

429
00:33:56,161 --> 00:33:59,079
[ Groans ]
[Ivan Laughing]
Come on!

430
00:34:05,754 --> 00:34:08,327
[Brinkman
Groaning]

431
00:34:08,423 --> 00:34:11,839
- [ Screaming ]
- [ Laughing ]

432
00:34:13,595 --> 00:34:15,671
quietly, gentlemen.

433
00:34:15,764 --> 00:34:17,721
This is a school night.

434
00:34:20,018 --> 00:34:23,683
Please! Please, no!
[Ivan ]
You like that! Eddie!

435
00:34:23,772 --> 00:34:25,681
Come here, Eddie!

436
00:34:30,904 --> 00:34:33,360
- [ Laughing ]
- [ Ivan Speaking Russian ]

437
00:34:33,448 --> 00:34:36,402
- Eat!
- [ Men Laughing ]

438
00:34:39,580 --> 00:34:41,489
[ Ivan ]
Eat! Eat!

439
00:34:49,965 --> 00:34:51,874
David!

440
00:34:55,470 --> 00:34:57,428
Oh, no.

441
00:34:59,224 --> 00:35:01,715
David?.

442
00:35:06,899 --> 00:35:09,187
Durant!

443
00:35:10,652 --> 00:35:12,894
[ Darkman ]
It can't be!

444
00:35:12,988 --> 00:35:16,606
He survived!
Robert G. Durant!

445
00:35:16,700 --> 00:35:20,401
Bring the Asian's finger.
It will make a nice
addition to my collection.

446
00:35:20,495 --> 00:35:22,405
[ Cackling ]

447
00:35:22,497 --> 00:35:25,415
[Durant's Voice Echoing]
He's a freak! He's a freak!
He's a freak! He's a freak!

448
00:35:25,501 --> 00:35:27,577
[ Darkman ]
No. No!

449
00:35:27,669 --> 00:35:29,828
Noooooo!

450
00:35:29,922 --> 00:35:31,914
[ Electricity
Crackling ]
Yes!

451
00:35:32,007 --> 00:35:34,463
Music to my ears,
gentlemen.

452
00:35:34,551 --> 00:35:37,007
Aah!
Beautiful.

453
00:35:37,554 --> 00:35:39,547
Beautiful.

454
00:35:42,351 --> 00:35:44,889
Remember,
this is just the prototype.

455
00:35:48,524 --> 00:35:50,682
[ Grunts ]
Get out of the way.

456
00:35:53,028 --> 00:35:55,601
- Power on.
- [Electricity Humming]

457
00:35:55,697 --> 00:35:58,105
- Safety off.
- [ Weapon Beeping]

458
00:35:58,200 --> 00:36:01,070
[ Electrical Cycling
Accelerating ]

459
00:36:17,177 --> 00:36:19,086
Boss!

460
00:36:23,058 --> 00:36:25,549
- [ Grunts ]
- Yes!

461
00:36:26,979 --> 00:36:30,395
- The dawning of a new day!
- Right on.

462
00:36:30,482 --> 00:36:32,807
Shoots a little
to the left.

463
00:36:32,901 --> 00:36:35,855
Still uses
a lot of juice.

464
00:36:35,946 --> 00:36:39,647
Happily, we may have
found the solution
to our power problem.

465
00:36:39,741 --> 00:36:42,149
[ Beeping ]

466
00:36:43,745 --> 00:36:46,663
[Durant ]
Mr. Druganov recently
joined our organization...

467
00:36:46,748 --> 00:36:49,584
after an unusually varied
career in the KGB.

468
00:36:49,668 --> 00:36:51,577
His connections
have afforded us access...

469
00:36:51,670 --> 00:36:54,505
to some exceptional relics
of the Cold War.

470
00:36:54,590 --> 00:36:56,629
Plutonium carbide
energy cells,

471
00:36:56,717 --> 00:36:59,753
courtesy of space program
of former Soviet Union.

472
00:36:59,845 --> 00:37:02,336
Each device is
miniature nuclear reactor...

473
00:37:02,431 --> 00:37:06,381
capable of generating
450 gigawatts.

474
00:37:07,644 --> 00:37:10,562
They were designed to be used
in spy satellites...

475
00:37:10,647 --> 00:37:12,557
Launched over
capitalist countries,

476
00:37:12,649 --> 00:37:15,686
but nobody's launching anymore
so Ivan gets these for us wholesale.

477
00:37:17,070 --> 00:37:19,146
Are they stable?.

478
00:37:19,239 --> 00:37:23,367
These cells were manufactured
by technicians in workers'
